{
  "text": "Our data analyses confirmed IR evolution in Rosales (Fig 7A) . The incomplete rps19 gene of Prunus in Rosaceae (Fig 7E) and Rhamnus in Rhamnaceae (Fig 7D) was duplicated in the IR region. Conversely, Morus in Moraceae did not contain a duplicated rps19 gene in the IR region (Fig 7B) . Only the Elaeagnaceae was duplicated in the trnH gene (Fig 7C) . The trnH gene duplication is a useful marker in Rosales, such as Dirachmacae, Barbeyaceae and Elaeagnaceae. In a previous study, Richardson et al. [CITATION_1] suggested a sister relationship between Rhamnaceae, Dirachmaceae and Barbeyaceae. In contrast, Zhang et al. [CITATION_2] suggested a sister relationship among Elaeagnaeae, Dirachmaceae and Barbeyaceae, but this was not well supported in the Elaeagnaceae clade. Consequently, analyses of trnH duplication in the LSC/IRb junction and the IRa/ LSC junction from different Moraceae and Elaeagnaceae would be of great value in systematics studies.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "13380939",
    "[CITATION_2]": "9309291"
